context: <a0_0>"<b4_0>New Labour<b4_0/>"<a0_0/> was first termed as an alternative branding for the Labour Party, dating from a conference slogan first used by the Labour Party in <a1_0><b5_0>1994<b5_0/><a1_0/>, which was later seen in a <b7_0>draft manifesto<b7_0/> published by the party in <a2_0>1996<a2_0/>, called <a3_0>New Labour, New Life For Britain<a3_0/>. It was a continuation of the trend that had begun under the leadership of <b6_0>Neil Kinnock<b6_0/>. "New Labour" as a name has no <b8_0>official<b8_0/> status, but remains in common use to distinguish modernisers from those holding to more traditional positions, normally referred to as "Old Labour".
